name: National service
summary: The Conservative Party in the United Kingdom plans to implement mandatory National Service for 18-year-olds. Rishi Sunak, a leading Conservative candidate for Prime Minister, has pledged to reintroduce the program if elected. The plan has garnered mixed reactions, with some supporting the idea of instilling discipline and patriotism in youth, while others express concerns about the cost and potential infringement on individual liberties. The proposal would require all 18-year-olds to participate in a six-month program of training and service, similar to the National Service system that existed in the UK until 1960. The Conservatives believe the program would foster a sense of national unity, promote civic responsibility, and prepare young people for future roles in society or the military.

name: Paul Weller
summary: Paul Weller's latest album, "66," has garnered critical acclaim, with reviewers praising its mature and introspective reflections on aging. The record is described as a "sumptuous rumination" (The Guardian) and a "middle-age adventure" (inews) that explores themes of mortality, identity, and the passage of time. The album features collaborations with a star-studded cast of musicians, including Noel Gallagher and Rod Argent, adding to its appeal (MOJO). Critics note that Weller's "grumpy old man" persona (The Telegraph) still shines through, but also highlight the album's surprising and experimental moments (The Guardian). Weller's post-show ritual of a cup of tea (Yahoo News UK) provides a glimpse into his current lifestyle, while the physical album release celebrates his milestone birthday (Genesis Publications).

name: Tom Holland
summary: Tom Holland's performance in the West End production of "Romeo & Juliet" has garnered mixed reviews. The Guardian praised Holland's entrance and Francesca Amewudah-Rivers' portrayal of Juliet, while the BBC acknowledged the positive audience response despite critical concerns. The Independent criticized Holland's performance as falling short. However, The Telegraph lauded Holland's mesmerizing performance and called the production a "once-in-a-generation" event. The Express condemned the production as "absolute drivel," while Time Out London praised Holland's acting despite the production's strange and dark nature. British Vogue commented on Holland's new Caesar cut, comparing it to George Clooney's in 1995. LondonTheatre.co.uk praised the production's sexiness, intensity, and haunting atmosphere. Holland's fans have had strong reactions to his new haircut, which has been compared to that of a footballer. Yahoo News UK speculated on a possible reference to Holland in the film "Challengers."

TalkSPORT's Graeme Souness expresses concern that Rashford could become a "great disappointment" in English football.
